 (Accepted 3 June 1993) 
 
 Abstract 
 
 This paper uses a flexible (translog) production function to guess (wasting very little while working or producing something) of 227 farms from West Bengal, 
 India. We think about/believe guess of technical and allocative inefficiencies using a (money made/good thing received) making the most of (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) which 
 changes something (to helps someone)/takes care of someone both endogenous and (coming from the outside of something) inputs. The maximum chance method of guess developed in 
 this paper is based on the production function and the first-order conditions of profit (biggest increase/best possible extent). Farm-specific 
 technical and allocative inefficiencies are also guessed. Scientific results show that the mean level of technical 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) is 75.46% while the best farm is 85.87% (producing a lot with very little waste) (technically). So far as allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) is concerned 
 most of the farms are found to be under-users of the endogenous inputs, that is,, fertiliser, poop/fertilizer, human and 
 little bull labour. 
 
 1. Introduction 
 
 The neoclassical explanation of production is based 
 on the idea of (wasting very little while working or producing something). This idea is focused in the textbook definition of a production 
 function which gives the maximum possible output for given amounts of inputs. One problem 
 with the idea of 'maximum' is that nobody can 
 recognise it simply by watching/ noticing/ celebrating/ obeying the actual level 
 of output unless the watched/followed output is assumed 
 to be the highest value. Such an idea (you think is true) is not 
 realistic since different producers do produce different levels of output even if they use the same 
 level of every watched/followed input. One way of explaining the difference in watched/followed outputs among 
 producers is through differences in productive 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something). In the edge of something/unexplored area approach a producer is 
 
 said to be technically (producing a lot with very little waste) 1 if the watched/followed 
 output is highest value, given the input amounts. 
 So, the production edge of something/unexplored area is defined as the 
 center  of maximum possible outputs for each level 
 of input use. A failure on the part of the farm to 
 produce the edge of something/unexplored area level of output, given the 
 input amounts, is attributed to technical inefficiency. 
 
 1 The idea  of technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) goes back to Farrell 
 (1957). Another idea  of (wasting very little while working or producing something) is Leibenstien's X-(wasting very little while working or producing something) (1966), which is often connected with poor quality or 
 poorly trained/motivated labour force, lack of managerial 
 effort, etc. In the big picture  of farming, soil (features/ qualities/ traits), 
 (related to the Earth's weather) and some (related to how much money and power people have) factors may affect (wasting very little while working or producing something) of a farm. 
 
