 Technical inefficiency is not the only inefficiency. If the producer makes mistakes in setting apart inputs, the resulting inefficiency is labeled as 
 allocative inefficiency. It is always connected with 
 some behavioral goal like profit (biggest increase/best possible extent) or cost minimisation. Mistakes in the portion of useful things/valuable supplies and production of (less-than-best) 
 level of output increase cost and, therefore, decrease (money made/good thing received). As a result, identification of the 
 inefficient producers is very important, especially 
 for government policy designed to (help increase/show in a good way) (producing a lot with very little waste) use of useful things/valuable supplies. 
 Econometric guess of edge of something/unexplored area functions 
 goes back to Aigner, Lovell and Schmidt (1977) 
 and Meeiisen and van den Broeck (1977). The 
 way(s) of doing things proposed by these authors is quite 
 general and can change something (to help someone)/take care of someone any functional 
 form of the hidden (under) production technology. 
 However, their approach is restricted to guess of only technical inefficiency or cost therefrom. Extensions of the Aigner et al. (1977) model 
 to includes both technical and allocative inefficiencies have been made in terms of production 
 functions for which the cost or the profit functions can be received/made from clearly from the optimising 
 conditions (see, for example, Schmidt and Lovell, 
 1979, 1980; Kumbhakar, 1987, 1988). The major 
 advantage of using such (serving to severely limit or control) production 
 functions lies in getting closed form math-related 
 formulae for costs of technical and allocative 
 inefficiencies which are of first (or most important) concern to the 
 producers. The disadvantage is that the production functions for which cost or profit functions 
 can be received/made from clearly are quite (serving to severely limit or control) in 
 nature. 
 This paper describes a method of guessing 
 technical and allocative inefficiencies using a 
 translog production function - the most widely 
 used flexible functional form in applied works. 
 Guessing a translog production function with 
 inefficiency was first proposed by Greene (1980). 
 He assumed, at least completely/in a hinting way, the inputs to be 
 (coming from the outside of something) or pre-planned. The problem with 
 such an idea (you think is true) is that allocative inefficiency 
 from (less-than-best) input use cannot arise since the 
 use of input levels are no longer a choice (number or thing that changes). 
 In this paper, we leave from the Greene 
 
 creation by including endogenous and (coming from the outside of something) inputs. The endogenous inputs are chosen 
 to (make as big as possible) expected value of (money made/good thing received). Since the 
 input demand and output supply functions cannot 
 be received/made from clearly, the limits/guidelines are guessed from the system of equations consisting of 
 the production function and the first-order conditions of expected profit (biggest increase/best possible extent) using the 
 Maximum Chance (ML) method. Guess 
 of technical and allocative inefficiencies for each 
 (instance of watching, noticing, or making a statement) is also thought about/believed. The proposed 
 method is applied to guess (wasting very little while working or producing something) of 227 
 farms in West Bengal, India. 
 Organisation of the rest of the paper is as 
 follows. Section 2 gives an summary of (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 studies in Indian farming. This is followed by 
 the econometric model. Section 4 describes the 
 data and the results are reported in Section 5. 
 End/end result and statements are in Section 6. 
 
 2. (wasting very little while working or producing something) measures in Indian farming 
 
 Previous studies on (wasting very little while working or producing something) of Indian farms 
 can be classified broadly into the following three 
 categories. First, studies based on the emotional  approach where the limits/guidelines were directly guessed mostly by using the ordinary least squares 
 (OLS) method. These limit/guideline guesses were 
 then used to check whether the first order conditions of profit (biggest increase/best possible extent) are happy (see, for 
 example, Hopper, 1965; Sahota, 1968; Saini, 
 1979). Attempts were also made to model these 
 mistakes in terms of (capable of being seen and known) factors like education, experience, etc. (Ram, 1980). In the second category of studies, (money made/good thing received) making the most of behavior was clearly taken into account by guessing 
 the dual profit function. Again (wasting very little while working or producing something) was 
 modeled as a function of farm (features/ qualities/ traits) like 
 size of land holding (Lau and Yotopoulos, 1971; 
 Yotopoulos and Lau, 1973), size and form of 
 (living somewhere) (Junankar, 1980), variety of crops, and 
 the degree of mechanisation (Sidhu, 1974). Finally, over the last few years the edge of something/unexplored area way(s) of doing things of 
 Aigner et al. (1977) was used by Huang and Bagi 
 (1984), Huang (1984) and Kalirajan and Shand 
 (1985), among others. 
 
 S.C. Kumbhakar /Agricultural Money flow 10 (1994) 143-152 
 
 The present study follows the last approach, 
 (in other words), it uses the (random/including random data points) edge of something/unexplored area method to 
 guess money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something) of farms in West 
 Bengal, India. We extend the results of previous 
 studies by incorporating allocative inefficiency together with technical inefficiency in a translog 
 production function. This extension has two major advantages. First, in contrast to the previous 
 edge of something/unexplored area studies, we do not assume all inputs to be 
 (coming from the outside of something) or pre-planned. Instead, we include 
 both (coming from the outside of something) and endogenous inputs in our 
 analysis. More than that, the idea (you think is true) that the endogenous inputs are independent of technical 
 inefficiency is not made. Second, we use a system 
 of (happening together) equations to avoid possible bias 
 that might arise due to the presence of the endogenous inputs and their relationships with technical inefficiency. 2 By including the first-order 
 conditions of profit (biggest increase/best possible extent) in the guess process we hope to get (producing more with less waste) limit/guideline guesses. 
 
 3. Econometric model 
 It is well known that the production technology can be guessed by either the emotional (direct) 
 or the dual (indirect) approach. In the dual approach, one starts with a (money made/good thing received) or cost function 
 which can be directly guessed. Added/more information can be gotten by using HotellingShephard's lemma. 3 In this paper we use the 
 emotional  approach where guess of the produc- 
 
 One can also avoid the endogeneity problem by guessing a 
 profit function. Since the input and output prices are (coming from the outside of something), consistent estimator of the limits/guidelines is received/got using 
 a single-equation way of doing things. There are, however, two problems connected with guessing a profit function. First, guess of profit function needs/demands price (quality of changing over time or at different places) which might 
 be a problem in a thin sliceal data (see, e.g., Junankar, 
 1989). Second, separating costs of technical and allocative 
 inefficiencies (in terms of previous/unavoidable (money made/good thing received)) from a profit function is not always possible. Since our goal is to guess 
 both technical and allocative inefficiencies, we decided not to 
 chase after the profit function approach in this study. 
