 4. Data 
 
 The data set used in the present study has 
 been collected by the Agro-Money-based Research 
 Centre 6 from three areas of the Indian state of 
 West Bengal. These areas cover the whole 
 paddy production belt of West Bengal. A crosssection random sample of 227 household farms 
 has been selected for the present study. The 
 survey was managed and did/done during 1980-1985. Since 
 different areas were surveyed in different years, 
 it is not a panel. Over the last twenty years, the 
 
 An farming-based research centre under the Ministry of Farming, Government of India. 
 6 
 
 147 
 
 coming of (related to computers and science) changes, introduction of 
 high cooperating with/producing/giving up seeds, security of land (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment), availability of production loans, relaxation of government control over (instance of buying something for money) of output and sale of 
 some important  factors (fertilisers, crop-watering/rinsing with water water, 
 bug-killers), etc., have made the farming-based production system very much market oriented. Under such an (surrounding conditions), use of the profit (biggest increase/best possible extent) guess on the part of the producers 
 as a maintained guess seems appropriate. 
 The farming-based production activities of the 
 state of West Bengal are spread over at least two 
 crop seasons. Here we think about/believe the bad rainstorm 
 paddy as our subject of (act of asking questions and trying to find the truth about something). 7 This choice 
 is because bad rainstorm paddy is produced by all farms in the area under (act of asking questions and trying to find the truth about something). More than that, during this season, markets for 
 the inputs become quite competitive. 
 Output (Y) is measured in quintals (100 kg) of 
 paddy. The endogenous inputs are: fertiliser (F), 
 poop/fertilizer (M), human labour (N) and little bull labour 
 (B). We treat land (L) and capital (K) as quasifixed inputs. The human labour includes both 
 family labour and hired labour and is measured 
 in hours. Little bull labour is also measured in hours. 
 Fertiliser and poop/fertilizer are measured in kg. Land 
 is measured in areas of land. Prices of paddy, fertiliser, 
 poop/fertilizer, labour and little bull labour are all measured in Indian rupees. 
 The capital (number or thing that changes) used here is a weighted 
 average of rental value of services from crop-watering/rinsing with water 
 and other farm equipment. The land under (producing crops/helping something grow) has been used as a almost-fixed input because its market is not well developed especially 
 in leasing out. It is measured in areas of land and it 
 includes the area under bad rainstorm paddy only. 
 Working well differences due to different types 
 of soil, land, weather and land sizes are controlled by including (related to a large area) and farm-size dummy 
 (numbers that change/things that change) in the production function. We hope 
 that these (related to a large area) dummies will (record by a camera or computer) the differential effects of soil, land and weather since 
 we do not have data on these (numbers that change/things that change). 
 
 7 Data on input usage are related to the production of paddy 
 only. Inputs used other than in paddy are not thought about/believed 
 here. 
 
