 Two different models, that is,, a single-equation translog 
 model and a (happening together) equation Cobb-Douglas (CD) 
 model, were also thought about/believed. About 90% of the limits/guidelines 
 were found to be (related to numbers) unimportant in the first model. 
 Because of this we did not chase after the single-equation translog 
 model further. The CD model is a special case of the translog 
 model thought about/believed in this study. We, therefore, test the restricÂ· 
 tions for the CD model using the chance ratio test. The 
 test rejects the CD (detailed description of exactly what is required) at the 1% level of signifiÂ· 
 cance. The distribution of technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) created from 
 this model shows much greater (quality of changing over time or at different places) - ranging from 20% 
 to 87% with a mean value of 67.13%. Since this model is 
 rejected by the data, we decided not to report the results in 
 details. 
