 are not surprised by the above results on technical (wasting very little while working or producing something). The mean level of technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) is just like other almost the same  studies. 9 
 There are, however, certain factors which can 
 affect the guess of technical (wasting very little while working or producing something). First, 
 since we are dealing with cross sectional data, 
 farm-clearly stated/particular factors cannot be controlled. So, 
 unseen farm effects are confused with 
 technical (wasting very little while working or producing something). As a result, farms which are 
 found to be most inefficient might not be so if 
 individual effects are controlled. This can be done 
 only when panel data are available [see, for example, Kumbhakar and Hjalmarsson (1993) for such 
 an application]. Second, the role of non-physical 
 inputs like experience, information, supervision, 
 etc., might influence the ability of a producer to 
 use the available technology (in a way that produces a lot with very little waste). These 
 factors are not taken into account because of 
 non-availability of such information in the present data. 
 To compose a management index that describes how management is reflected in the level 
 of input use, we run an extra/helping (thing) moving backward 
 of technical (wasting very little while working or producing something), which can be used as an 
 index of 'management', on all of the inputs. 10 
 The results show positive relationship between 
 technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) and (endogenous) input use. 
 In other words, an inefficient farm tends to use 
 less of every (endogenous) input and produce less 
 output (Kumbhakar, 1987). This finding suggests 
 that: 
 - The OLS results based on the production function without the management (number or thing that changes) are (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking). 
 - Even if technical inefficiency is introduced into 
 the analysis [as in Huang and Bagi (1984), 
 Huang (1984), Kalirajan and Shand (1985), 
 among others], the idea (you think is true) that technical 
 inefficiency is independent of the inputs is 
 inappropriate. As a result, the limit/guideline 
 guesses are (not agreeing/not happening in the same way) if the production 
 function alone is used in guess. 
 See the survey by Battese (1992) and the references referred to 
 there for a variety of applications in farming-based money flow/money-based studies 
 using data from different countries. 
