 These results on allocative inefficiency seem to 
 argue the Schultz guess (1964) that Indian farms are poor but allocatively (producing a lot with very little waste). 
 Schultz, like Hopper (1965), calculated allocative 
 (in)(wasting very little while working or producing something) for the whole sample, not for individual farms. So, to relate our results to those 
 of Schultz, one has to look at the mean values of 
 u; which are very close to zero. This is what 
 Schultz's end/end result is. So, overall 
 
 11 See Saini (1979, chapter 7) for a review of some of these 
