 6. End/end result and statements 
 
 The main (thing that's given/work that's done) of this paper is in the 
 use of a flexible (translog) production function in 
 guessing technical and allocative (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) using farm-level data from West Bengal, India. We 
 used the expected profit (biggest increase/best possible extent) judging requirement 
 which changes something (to helps someone)/takes care of someone both endogenous and (coming from the outside of something) (almost-fixed) inputs and guessed both 
 technical and allocative inefficiencies for each 
 farm. The possibility of bias or (unexpected difference, missing thing, or mistake) in 
 limit/guideline guesses resulting from relationship of 
 technical inefficiency and input use is eliminated 
 by using a (happening together) equation approach instead of a single equation method. 
 The scientific results show that there is big scope for improving technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 of these farms. None of the farms in our sample 
 is fully technically (producing a lot with very little waste). The (producing the most with the least waste) 
 farm is about 14% below the production edge of something/unexplored area. 
 We also find that technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) is positively 
 related to fertiliser, poop/fertilizer, labour and little bull labour but negatively with land size. The last 
 result shows that small farms are (producing more with less waste) 
 (technically). This finding is important so far as 
 the land reform policy of the government is con- 
 
 !51 
 
 cerned. Concerning allocative inefficiency, we find 
 that more than 50% of the farms in our sample 
 under-use fertiliser, poop/fertilizer, labour and little bull labour. The extent of under-use, however, 
 differs/changes from farm to farm. This thing/event of 
 inefficient use of inputs may be due to distortions 
 in the input and output markets resulting from 
 government rules as well as social and cultural restrictions. (not totally pure/not totally correct) market conditions 
 may also be responsible for this misallocation. 
 The present research can be extended in a few ways. First, factors like land size, land (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment), 
 credit availability, education, extension services, 
 etc., may be introduced to explain differences in 
 technical and allocative (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste). Second, if 
 the product and factor markets are not competitive because of government rules, social 
 and cultural (blocking things), etc., or some of the factors 
 are not moving and farms are risk disliking, (something forced on people/an inconvenient situation) of the expected profit (biggest increase/best possible extent) (risk 
 neutrality) guess may lead to wrong ends/end results, especially (related to/looking at/thinking about) allocative inefficiency. Finally, availability of panel data would be 
 helpful to control for farm-clearly stated/particular effects which 
 cannot be separated from technical inefficiency 
 using cross sectional data. We hope to face/deal with 
 some of these issues in the future. 
 
